LASSA FEVER - WEST AFRICA (21): NIGERIA (TARABA)
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 24 Mar 2016
Source: The News [edited]
http://thenewsnigeria.com.ng/2016/03/7-lassa-fever-suspects-on-the-run-in-taraba/


Seven suspected Lassa fever patients on admission at the Federal Medical Centre in Jalingo, capital of Taraba State, have vanished. Dr Aisha Sani, Chairperson, Lassa Fever Committee at the medical centre disclosed this today [24 Mar 2016], saying that government is making frantic efforts to arrest the suspects.

Sani said: "Seven persons had absconded. We are making frantic efforts to arrest and bring them back to the hospital before they infect others with the disease. We have our internal securities here, but the truth is that we need more to secure the Lassa fever unit."

So far, the deadly Lassa fever has claimed 14 lives in the state from January 2016 to date [24 Mar 2016]. About 80 people have died in Nigeria, overall.

According to Aisha, of the 49 suspected cases of the disease reported in the hospital, 21 persons were treated and discharged. The doctor said laboratory tests had so far confirmed 4 cases of the disease, while 4 suspected cases were referred to the Institute of Lassa Fever Research and Control, Irrua, Edo.

"The 4 patients had already developed kidney failure, and you know we don't have a dialysis section here. Let me use this medium to appeal to the Federal Government to provide a dialysis unit in this hospital so that we can save lives," she said.

Aisha said the hospital was currently handling 2 cases of the disease, adding that the worst affected areas in the state were Jalingo, Ardo-Kola and Bali local government areas.

The FMC officially confirmed the 1st death of 3 persons with Lassa fever disease on 5 Jan [2016].

