[Lassa fever is endemic in many of Nigeria's states, including Tabara. Apparently, the 7 patients who fled the hospital became infected before they were admitted and not in the hospital.

The virus is a member of the family _Arenaviridae_ and causes acute hemorrhagic fever. It is transmitted to humans from contacts with food or household items contaminated with excreta of multimammate mice (_Mastomys_ spp.), as was likely the case with these infected individuals. Virus transmission can occur in houses or in hospital environments or laboratories in the absence of adequate infection-control measures. Because there can be person-to-person transmission via contact with viremic blood or secretions of infected patients, adequate patient isolation and use of personal protection equipment for treatment of infected patients, as depicted in a photograph in the above report, are essential for safety. That is why the hospital is anxious for the 7 infected individuals who fled to return to the hospital where they can be placed in isolation. If they have returned to their homes, family members attending them and in contact with blood and other bodily fluids are at risk of infection themselves.

Prevention and control of Lassa fever in nature depends on control of the rodent reservoir, the multimammate mouse (_Mastomys_ spp.), which occurs across Nigeria and beyond. Reduction of populations of this rodent will require active participation at the village level. That will necessitate mounting a public education program with support of rodent control technicians. There has been no indication that a village-level control effort has been initiated yet.

Images of _Mastomys_ mice can be seen at http://www.ispot.org.za/node/255877.

Maps of Nigeria can be accessed at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/nigeria.pdf and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4123464,62. - Mod.TY]
